    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_30393406" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/30393406" />
    <a title="Tracey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/841949-tracey"><img alt="Tracey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325394892p2/841949.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/30393406?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tracey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tracey" href="/user/show/841949-tracey">Tracey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/841949-tracey?shelf=4-star">4-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/841949-tracey?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/841949-tracey?shelf=mercenaries">mercenaries</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer30393406" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13501596352929423677">I reread Legend for a group read, wanted to keep going… Another book, another siege. I hesitate to say this, but here goes: these first three books of the Chronicles of the Drenai tend to blur together a bit for me. It&apos;s true <i>The King Beyond the Gate</i>&apos;s Tenaka Khan is very different from Waylander in some ways - but not in others; Waylander was in turn in some ways (though not others) strongly reminiscent of Druss. The overarching plotlines were different, the allies and enemies different, but … </span>
  <span id="freeText13501596352929423677" style="display:none">I reread Legend for a group read, wanted to keep going… Another book, another siege. I hesitate to say this, but here goes: these first three books of the Chronicles of the Drenai tend to blur together a bit for me. It's true <i>The King Beyond the Gate</i>'s Tenaka Khan is very different from Waylander in some ways - but not in others; Waylander was in turn in some ways (though not others) strongly reminiscent of Druss. The overarching plotlines were different, the allies and enemies different, but … Here are more ruined fortresses and pillaged villages, more they-can-never-win battles, more insuperable opponents, and another monstrous body count. For me it did not pay to read the books back-to-back; the time jumps between stories were too disconcerting, especially with the connecting thread of the Armor of Bronze. The formula is so strong and, after two books, familiar that the occasional jaunts away from that formula were disorienting. (The worst of both worlds, that.)<br /> <br />Also, while the writing was still strong and spare and good, this time around I noticed some words that caused a bit of a jolt: i.e, e.g.: “ricochet” (the etymology for which is from the French (of course), in the later 1700's). (It isn’t a good example, but I didn’t make note of others; there might have been examples in the other books which I simply never registered.) I've ranted before about the use of inappropriate language (in terms of anachronisms and words too readily identified with their original language, not in terms of profanity), and the Drenai books didn't push me to the level of ranting; it was merely that there were occasional words used which gave me a small bump out of the story and the world it was set in: <i>they don't have French there</i> or <i>they shouldn't be aware of that concept</i>.<br /> <br />There is a strong division between black and white in the Drenai Tales: the bad guys kill little girls, the good guys grow roses. And it’s literal: you have the shining silver Thirty and the black-clad Hounds. And in between, a conflicted “hero”, or anti-hero – or a hero without internal conflict so much as herded by fate somewhere he would never have chosen to go. It was very strange to read about a half-Nadir main character, having finished <i>Legend</i> just before reading this; still, he's a good character, and the internal codes are not violated because nearly everyone in the book hates Tenaka Khan, Drenai and Nadir alike. <br /> <br />The Joinings were another source of unease for me – apart from the obvious reasons, I mean. Yes, they're horrible creatures, especially once you're given the background of exactly what they are; but that's not what I was thinking of. They are introduced early in the book, and are such a drastic departure from everything that has gone before that I was taken aback. It took quite a while to come to the explanation for them.<br /> <br />I'll continue on with the series after a while – I think I'll benefit from a break. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13501596352929423677" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


