<span id="freeTextContainer1602379241766448862">Vote: 3,25<br/>Class: L-B2 (FP)<br/><br/>I was positively impressed by the first book of the Drenai Saga (The Legend). It captivated me.<br/>I pinpointed some shortcomings of that book but I really hoped that they would be addressed by The King Beyond the Gate.<br/>Well, they weren&apos;t. It&apos;s a good book, not an awesome one.<br/><br/>The World (2,50) is the same of the first book and it lacks too many details about its history, its geografy, and its languages. They can&apos;t all simply speak the same language, you can&apos;t tell me of some </span>
  <span id="freeText1602379241766448862" style="display:none">Vote: 3,25<br />Class: L-B2 (FP)<br /><br />I was positively impressed by the first book of the Drenai Saga (The Legend). It captivated me.<br />I pinpointed some shortcomings of that book but I really hoped that they would be addressed by The King Beyond the Gate.<br />Well, they weren't. It's a good book, not an awesome one.<br /><br />The World (2,50) is the same of the first book and it lacks too many details about its history, its geografy, and its languages. They can't all simply speak the same language, you can't tell me of some machines they found of a lost past. What past? Why lost? How they were discovered? And so on.<br /><br />The characters (3.50) are good. They will win you. Some others are a bit too shallow.<br /><br />The plot (3,00) is (almost) good. The only thing is that it seems an episode disconnected from the story of the World: it didn't leave anything behind.<br /><br />The style (4.00) is very nice and smooth.<br /><br />Overall you can say: a good fantasy book, if you don't know what to read, you can read it but do not expect anything extraordinary.</span>
